tely redesigned: mid-engined Ferraris have returned to the scheme with four round lights instead of two, the shape of the spoiler has been changed. All interior elements are new, but the basic layout of the front panel is the same. And the main innovation is the seven—inch touchscreen of the media system in front of the passenger.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Carbon fiber and other ultralight materials are not used as widely in the Tributo model as in the Pista coupe. Therefore, the dry weight of the novelty is greater: 1330 kg instead of 1280 kg. Although if compared with the outgoing base coupe Ferrari 488 GPIB, the new car has become lighter by 40 kg. Therefore, the dynamic parameters are also \"in the middle of the range\". The Ferrari F8 Tributo can accelerate to 100 km/h in 2.9 seconds versus 3.0 seconds for the former coupe and 2.85 seconds for the Pista version. Acceleration to 200 km/h takes 7.8 seconds, while the Ferrari 488 GTB does it in 8.3 seconds, and the Pista in 7.6 seconds. The maximum speed is more than 340 km/h.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The first public display of the Ferrari F8 Tribute coupe will take place at the Geneva Motor Show, and sales will traditionally begin in the second half of the year. And a completely new mid-engined supercar is still not far off: the car with the code F173 should be shown in May, and it will have a hybrid drive and be positioned half a step above the Tributo model.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->', 'Ferrari F8 Tributo Supercar: Italy\'s evolution continues', 'First, in 2009, the Ferrari 458 Italia appeared, then, six years later, it was turned into the 488 GTB model. And now… the long-awaited new car? Alas, no. The company decided to change the traditions and continued the modernization of the former supercar. Moreover, in fact, the Ferrari F8 Tributo coupe is a \"disguised\" special version of the 488 Pista, which debuted a year ago.', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '579-revision-v1', '', '', '2022-10-02 22:47:01', '2022-10-02 19:47:01', '', 579, 'http://wordpress-carbook-training.ru/?p=586', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(587, 2, '2022-10-02 22:55:52', '2022-10-02 19:55:52', '<!-- wp:paragraph {\"align\":\"left\"} -->\n<p class=\"has-text-align-left\">The RML 250 car is a strange mix of a Ferrari 550 Maranello and a short—wheelbase 250 GT Berlinetta of 1959, or 250 SWB, as it is commonly called. It was created by RML, based in Northamptonshire, England, and costs $ 1.6 million. RML will create only 30 copies, and this is an obvious stylization designed to \"pump out\" millions of dollars from the rich and stupid. Or at least those who have a silly desire to always have something different from their billionaire buddies, regardless of cost or concept. The Ferrari-based RML 250 SWB is certainly different from its base element, but why does it exist at all?</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>That\'s why</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>RML CEO Michael Malloch says with a grin: \"We started as a racing team and were reborn into an engineering company working for OEM. Without the high-profile presence in motorsport that we once had, and since most of our work is invisible to the public and manufacturers that we don\'t work with, we needed a project that would show the full range of our capabilities.\"</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>This is a good answer and sounds true, but the next part is even more eloquent.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>\"There\'s something to be proud of here, too,\" Mallock adds. \"The first Mallock was built in 1958 and we are one of the oldest independent manufacturers in the UK. I\'m proud of this legacy, and I\'m really proud of this car. There will be other limited series projects.\"</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>What is RML?</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>RML\'s history and reputation give 250 SWB instant credibility. The history of the automotive family began with Arthur Milk, Michael\'s grandfather, an excellent racer in the 40s and 50s, who introduced the Mallock U2 special in 1958. The lightweight spaceframe chassis, designed to be tough and durable, was the most important and affordable for any enthusiast. Customers could buy a U2 chassis for 48 pounds and 10 shillings (about $120 at the time), install it with their own mechanics, usually from an Austin 7, and race. It has been developed over the years and dozens of U2s are still competing in the UK in various series with great success. It\'s like about a kind of single-seat Lotus Seven.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The history of motorsport continued with Ray Mallock, Michael\'s father, a talented racer and engineer. He founded Ray Mallock Limited (RML) in 1984 and things got more serious. From Group C cars and the success of Le Mans with the Aston Martin Nimrod project to various factory programs in the British Touring Car series and World Touring Car, RML has accumulated vast experience and an enviable reputation. He also designed the Nissan Deltawing Le Mans project and recently designed, engineered and produced the NIO EP9 EV hypercar, which ran a lap at the Nurburgring in just 6 minutes 45.9 seconds. At the other end of the scale, RML is the builder of the Bizzarrini 5300 GT Revival Corsa continuation cars. The project will see the creation of 24 new versions of the wonderful racing car of the 1960s, designed by Giotto Bizzarrini, the father of the Ferrari 250 GTO.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In other words, RML has competed at the highest level and is now working with OEMs on engineering projects, electric car technology and secret things he can\'t talk about. Its short 250 wheelbase is a way to get out of anonymity, showcase your engineering prowess and limited production experience, and have a lot of fun.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The 250 also fits perfectly with the growing movement towards more analog driving experiences. \"At the beginning of this project, the car was ready to become a hypercar,\" says Mallock. \"You know the score: a carbon bath, downforce loads, more than 1000 hp are completely unusable and meaningless on the road. Then I realized that I just didn\'t find the concept interesting. So we thought of something a little different.\"</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>Impressive details</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In the glorious blue Tour de France and with flawless panel gaps, no one will ever guess that this RML 250 SWB is a prototype. The car will undergo the same durability tests as the OEM limited edition car, including hot and cold tests and thousands of heavy kilometers at high speeds on Belgian cobblestones and on various test tracks to test the dynamics and guarantee durability.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>All these details fit perfectly into the unique driving environment. The driver sits next to the vertical windshield, as in the classic 250 or any of the amazing racing cars of the 50s and 60s from Jaguar, Aston Martin or Ferrari. Despite the fact that the SWB retains the basic interior of the 550 Maranello and the suspension arrangement, there is a real sense of similarity. The 5.5-liter V-12 engine is removed, rebuilt and painted in blue. However, RML resisted the urge to install racing-style engine management software to get more horses. This is not a car that is too concerned with straight-line speed, however, with 479 hp at 7000 rpm (RML found that donor cars have an average of about 420 hp before the upgrade), pushing about 1723 kg of weight, it should be able to accelerate to 295 km/h. SWB It has also been carefully modeled using CFD tools to ensure high-speed stability.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The sound of the motor is quite non-standard. Mallock wanted a classic V-12 howl at high revs: high, layered and clean. Oddly enough, the 550 Maranello is relatively quiet, and it tends to be quite booming and unpleasant when equipped with a sports exhaust, providing a flat roar instead of a complex symphony. RML 250 SWB fixes this problem.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>We are at the Millbrook Proving Ground on the infamous Alpine Hill route. The road here rises, rises and falls like a roller coaster, and the RML 250 SWB behaves easily and intuitively. The steering may be too light, but it pulsates gently with feedback. The structure seems rigid and modern, but the fluidity of the suspension is something else. Not classic, exactly, but certainly more focused on feedback and weight transfer and a kind of natural athleticism than any modern GT or sports car or, indeed, a Ferrari 550 Maranello equipped with a Fiorano control package. After giving the V-12 full freedom, the hood will rise and stretch to the horizon. In turns, pitch and roll are well controlled, and the car never feels like a tumbler. But compared to something like the Mustang GT350R or the modern Porsche, it\'s a much lighter car. The driver really dictates how the SWB will behave, and the sense of control is fascinating.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Dynamically, the car is completely attractive, but there is much more. In fact, the entire two-piece body of the SWB clamshell is made of carbon fiber, which provides additional rigidity compared to the 550 and significantly saves weight. RML admits that a full carbon fiber chassis would be ideal, but in order to sell the 250 short wheelbase worldwide and take into account all the sporting rules, it was necessary to keep the minimum from the 550 Maranello donor.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Those thighs, anyway. And a physical, precise gearbox. Noise. Rich and cultured, and thanks to the relatively short transmission, you can hear it turn again and again into a special, piercing cry of V-12. Or you can just choose third or fourth gear and control the torque.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->', 'RML Ferrari 250 SWB: $1.6 million car', 'The RML 250 car is a strange mix of a Ferrari 550 Maranello and a short—wheelbase 250 GT Berlinetta of 1959, or 250 SWB, as it is commonly called. It was created by RML, based in Northamptonshire, England, and costs $ 1.6 million. RML will create only 30 copies, and this is an obvious stylization designed to \"pump out\" millions of dollars from the rich and stupid. Or at least those who have a silly desire to always have something different from their billionaire buddies, regardless of cost or concept. The Ferrari-based RML 250 SWB is certainly different from its base element, but why does it exist at all?', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'rml-ferrari-250-swb-1-6-million-car', '', '', '2022-10-02 22:57:59', '2022-10-02 19:57:59', '', 0, 'http://wordpress-carbook-training.ru/?p=587', 0, 'post', '', 0),
