(592, 2, '2022-10-02 23:04:12', '2022-10-02 20:04:12', '<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Yes, surprisingly it is a plug-in hybrid with a turbocharged V-6 engine. But the only motorists who will hate Ferrari 296 GTB 2023, and who will loudly declare the release of the model a betrayal of all that is holy in the house of a Prancing Horse, are those who will never have the opportunity to get behind the wheel of such a car. Because if they really drove it, they would know: the 296 GTB is one of the greatest mid—engined Ferrari sports cars ever created.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>It certainly looks decent, has excellent proportions, and is created with a subtle homage to the mid-engined 250LM of the 1960s, including installed curvy rear seats and a vertical rear screen. Overall, the 296 GTB is one of the most compact and sporty cars from Maranello in recent times.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>As with the front—engined Roma, the 296 GTB taillights are transitioning from the traditional round Ferrari format - a move that required big sales from its own design team. A large central exhaust pipe adds visual and sonic drama. The only active part of the aerodynamic equipment is the vertical spoiler, which unfolds at speed or when braking, was cunningly packed to slip out from under the lights.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>But, but… a turbocharged six-cylinder hybrid powertrain? Seriously? This is quite a big step down in the power index compared to the roaring atmospheric V-8 and V-12 that made Ferrari famous. However, let\'s be clear: although the 296 GTB may be Ferrari\'s first six—cylinder road car in history - the magnificent little Dino 206 and 246, built between 1967 and 1974, do not count because they were never sold as Ferraris.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>And outwardly, of course, this car does not look like a six-cylinder car.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>About the engine</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The compact 2.9-liter twin-turbocharged V-6, codenamed F163, which underlies the 296 GTB powerplant, has a wide-angle 120-degree angle with fast-reacting turbochargers rotating in the opposite direction, mounted in the exhaust manifold and air intakes outside the cylinder heads. The wide-angle camber of the cylinders not only reduces the center of gravity by reducing the height between the tops of the cylinder heads and the forged crankshaft, but also provides the engine with a symmetrical starting order.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>As a result, the F163 rotates smoothly with a speed limiter of 8500 rpm, generating third-order harmonics similar to the harmonics of the V-12, the sound of which Ferrari engineers amplified with the help of a patented \"hot exhaust pipe\" system that captures the exhaust sound before hot gases enter the catalytic converters. And the motor really sounds like a V-12. Full throttle is all you need to understand why Ferrari engineers started calling the F163 engine \"piccolo V-12\" during development.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The 296 GTB is also the first rear-wheel drive plug-in hybrid from Ferrari with an electric motor/generator, dubbed the MGU-K by Ferrari in honor of its F1 hybrid technology installed between the V-6 engine and a compact new eight-speed dual-clutch transmission. An evolution of the electric motor used in the SF90, the MGU-K 296 GTB develops 165 horsepower and a maximum torque of 232 Nm, which is 20 percent more.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The MGU-K can allow the 296 GTB to travel up to 24 kilometers on clean electricity, powered by a 7.45 kWh battery pack that is installed along the entire car between the cab and the engine. But its main task is to ensure that the torque is filled at low revs and increase the power at higher revs. By itself, the F163 develops 654 horsepower with a specific power of 218 hp per liter, which is a new record for the internal combustion engine of a production car. Due to the fact that the MGU-K extends a helping hand to the gasoline engine in difficult moments, as a result, the 296 GTB produces powerful 818 horsepower at 8000 rpm and 546 Nm of torque at 6250 rpm.. Wow..</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The interaction between the internal combustion engine and the MGU-K has been carefully tuned so that the transmission provides a rapid acceleration jump up to the red line, which is a hallmark of the best atmospheric 12-cylinder Ferrari engines. The instantaneous torque of the electric motor is adjusted for each transmission to ensure maximum linear torque delivery. \"We are not using the entire powertrain at the lower level yet,\" confirms Ferrari test and development pilot Raffaele de Simone. \"The machine can do more.\"</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>What is he capable of</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Ferrari claims that the 296 GTB will accelerate from 0 to 100 km/h in less than 2.9 seconds and to 200 km/h in 7.3 seconds on the way to a top speed of more than 330 km/h. But these numbers don\'t even come close to describing the extraordinary power and flexibility of its powertrain. So, in sixth gear, the 296 GTB pulls cleanly and strongly from 1400 rpm — about 50 km/h — to … well, we don\'t know for sure, because we drove off the road at 234 km/h, the revs are still growing.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>A quick preliminary calculation shows that the Ferrari had another 40 km/h to accelerate before the engine reached a peak power of 8000 rpm. This is an operating speed range of more than 225 km/h. In one gear.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>This flexibility means that, although the gear ratios of the eight-speed gearbox are perfectly distributed, it is not necessary to put the right gear in order to force the 296 GTB to come out of turns abruptly. There is torque and there is power when needed. And it\'s not just a transmission that will make anyone choke on acceleration. The 296 GTB chassis is also no less perfect.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The 102.4-inch wheelbase of the 296 GTB is the shortest in the current Ferrari lineup, and the compact dimensions have been specially chosen to ensure maximum maneuverability. The new EPS system, first used on a rear-wheel drive Ferrari, is twice as inferior to previously used hydraulic systems, improves steering response, and the knowledge gained from the EPS-equipped SF90 allowed Ferrari to carefully configure it to filter out unwanted road bumps, while maintaining maximum sensation and feedback.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>Finish line</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The transitions between e-motor and ICE are smooth. This is a Ferrari that you can drive with pleasure every day. The digital cockpit offers the graphic splendor and high-tech smartphone connectivity you\'d expect from a modern luxury car, and the \"rough road\" feature, available at the touch of a switch, smoothes the ride when the asphalt gets rough. The 296 GTB is available with a seven-year Ferrari maintenance package, and maintenance intervals are set once a year or every 30,000 km.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The 296 GTB is the product of a cool—headed Ferrari at the pinnacle of development: a Ferrari that is not afraid to use advanced, even controversial technologies to create sports cars with the best performance, better handling and a better driving experience.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The first cars are due to go on sale in the third quarter of this year at an MSRP of $317,986.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->', 'Ferrari 296 GT 2023 Test Drive: Plug-in Hybrid and V6', 'Yes, surprisingly it is a plug-in hybrid with a turbocharged V-6 engine. But the only motorists who will hate Ferrari 296 GTB 2023, and who will loudly declare the release of the model a betrayal of all that is holy in the house of a Prancing Horse, are those who will never have the opportunity to get behind the wheel of such a car. Because if they really drove it, they would know: the 296 GTB is one of the greatest mid—engined Ferrari sports cars ever created.', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'ferrari-296-gt-2023-test-drive-plug-in-hybrid-and-v6', '', '', '2022-10-02 23:04:12', '2022-10-02 20:04:12', '', 0, 'http://wordpress-carbook-training.ru/?p=592', 0, 'post', '', 0),
