(606, 2, '2022-10-03 22:38:50', '2022-10-03 19:38:50', '<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Between the debut of a brand new car and its replacement with a completely redesigned model, it usually gets a \"mid-cycle update\". The manufacturer is updating several easily replaceable parts, such as bumpers and exterior lights, in order to achieve a slightly fresher appearance (hence the term \"update\"), and also possibly changes some color solutions, wheel design and new features. Usually all this is enough to extend the relevance of the car for several more years. By 2023, BMW has unveiled its relatively new three-row luxury SUV X7: a brand new dashboard topped with the latest displays, replacement of six- and eight-cylinder engines with new ones and offering the first ever 23-inch wheels of the brand. The model range is reduced from three main variants to two: the six-cylinder X7 xdrive40d and the eight-cylinder X7 M60.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>The appearance of the BMW X7 is hard to miss…</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>We have a theory: all this novelty serves as a counterweight to the most exciting update of the BMW X7 2023 — its appearance. We\'re not saying there\'s a conspiracy, but just look at the X7. BMW goes way beyond the usual mid-cycle stream of changes in the three years of the new 2019 X7, which makes us rub our chins and think maybe there were some doubts in Munich about how the brutalist mug would play with clients.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In the end, BMW designers mixed the pre-updated X7 headlights, fog lights, air intakes and radiator grilles in a blender, and then sprayed it all over the nose of the SUV in the style of Jackson Pollock. The processing mimics what BMW did with the latest 7-series sedan and its electric counterpart, the i7. We\'re still not quite sure what to do with all this, but one thing is for sure: the new X7 is hard to miss.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>Moving forward …</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The interior of the 2023 BMW X7 remains more cramped among full-size luxury three-row SUVs, but BMW\'s changes overall have made it much nicer. Handling The ride quality is improved thanks to a reconfigured (and standard) air suspension, adaptive shock absorbers and steering on the rear wheels (standard for the M60, optional for the xDrive40i), as well as a pair of new engines that replace last year\'s turbocharged I-6 and a V-shaped engine with dual turbocharging. The six-cylinder model X7, leading in terms of sales, retains its name xdrive40e, the V8 model received a new xDrive M60 badge.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>During our trip to the BMW plant in Spartanburg, South Carolina, where the company produces its X-branded SUV models for America and other global markets, we spent most of our time in the xDrive40i. The low revs of the 523-horsepower M60 confirmed how strong the I-6 engine is. The six-cylinder engine itself is not new, but it is new to the X7 and runs on a Miller combustion cycle to reduce fuel consumption, in addition to a sporty 48-volt soft hybrid amplifier. It produces 40 hp. more than the inline six it replaces, resulting in its total power reaching 375 hp and 539 Nm of torque. Most of the X7s are equipped in this way, and now they are rushing forward with pleasure and great power to fulfill family responsibilities (and not only — forward, parents will be able to have a little fun by pressing the gas pedal). BMW claims that the new six-cylinder X7 accelerates 0.5 seconds faster to 100 km/h, reaching this speed in 5.8 seconds. As always, the BMW transmission polish is excellent: the I-6 emits a muffled but pleasant growl and almost does not vibrate, and also perfectly combines with the reconfigured eight-speed automatic transmission.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The 4.4-liter V-8 M60 engine is also new, but produces the same 523 hp and 749 Nm of torque as the old X7 M50i engine. The previously available X7 xDrive50i with a V-8 with less power disappears from the lineup. For the owner of the M60, a good reason for such high power should be important before spending money on it, although the car also comes with a lot of M performance characteristics and a more rigid suspension setup. Oh, and the radiator grilles on the nose light up. Both the I-6 and V-8 are supplemented with a 48-volt hybrid installation, including a 12-horsepower electric motor with a torque of 200 Nm, located between the internal combustion engine and the transmission. This not only increases the torque at low engine speeds, but also ensures a smooth stop and start of the engine to save fuel when stationary. By the way, both engines are more efficient than the ones they replace, increasing fuel economy in all directions.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>BMW is proud of the new 23-inch wheels, the first such rim size for the brand, and although we probably abandoned them. The xDrive40i, which we did most of the test drive with, had big 23s, and with the exception of some tire bumps on the compensators and increased tire noise in general, they didn\'t seem to have much impact on the ride, which was more comfortable and better insulated than before.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>What\'s inside</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The interior of the 2023 BMW X7 has undergone even more thorough changes, now with a new dashboard with a 12.3-inch digital dashboard and a 14.9-inch touchscreen from the iX electric SUV. These two displays are on the same curved glass panel, leaving very few physical buttons elsewhere on the dashboard. The volume control is located next to some controls under the center screen, the headlight controls are located to the left of the steering wheel — and that\'s it. The center console has a start button, as well as height adjustment, motion mode and keyboard shortcuts (plus the iDrive control knob) for the key menu.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Integrating what BMW calls its \"operating system 8,\" which is both the software and hardware designation for its newest displays and their underlying electrical architecture, has been more challenging than finding a place to install these screens. Regardless of the effort, the result looks effortless — these screens look like they\'ve always been here. While the displays of some updated cars added later may look strange, the brand new X7 dashboard looks like it was designed from the beginning with these displays in mind. The graphics on the screens are as clear as the touch screen\'s response to input.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Standard equipment is also becoming more generous: each X7 gets heated front seats, a SensaTec dashboard (covered with artificial leather), comfortable keyless access, a panoramic sunroof, four-zone climate control and a wireless phone charger.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->', 'BMW X7 2023 Review: Newer than It Looks', 'Between the debut of a brand new car and its replacement with a completely redesigned model, it usually gets a \"mid-cycle update\". The manufacturer is updating several easily replaceable parts, such as bumpers and exterior lights, in order to achieve a slightly fresher appearance (hence the term \"update\"), and also possibly changes some color solutions, wheel design and new features. Usually all this is enough to extend the relevance of the car for several more years. By 2023, BMW has unveiled its relatively new', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'bmw-x7-2023-review-newer-than-it-looks', '', '', '2022-10-03 22:38:50', '2022-10-03 19:38:50', '', 0, 'http://wordpress-carbook-training.ru/?p=606', 0, 'post', '', 0),
