(612, 2, '2022-10-04 22:19:02', '2022-10-04 19:19:02', '<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>By the end of this decade, the 5.2-liter twin-turbocharged Aston Martin V-12 engine, originally installed in 2016 under the hood of the DB11 coupe, will go down in the history books as the most \"strangled\" by ever-increasing emissions standards and fuel consumption restrictions. But in the Aston Martin V12 Vantage of 2023, the engine has not become weaker, its nature is raging, turning an interesting entry-level sports car into a sparkling supercar.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>With a 690 hp engine and 752 Nm of torque under a radically redesigned hood, the Vantage 2023 is the most powerful car in the series ever built, and boasts excellent efficiency and power, for example, the Honda Civic powerplant is weaker by 163 horsepower, to be precise, and the V12 Vantage S. of the previous generation, concedes 124 horses. It is also the fastest, with a claimed acceleration time of 0-100 km/h in 3.4 seconds, and the fastest of the current Vantage lineup with a top speed of 321 km/h (200 mph).</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>What\'s new</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The 2023 V12 Vantage is more than just last year\'s version with a new engine. Changes to the suspension include a new adaptive damping system, a revised bushing and stiffer front upper mounts. The overall rigidity of the body was increased due to additional front and rear panels, rear suspension strut struts and fuel tank mounts.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Its track was widened by 4.04 centimeters, and the spring damping speed was increased by 50 percent on the front axle and 40 percent on the rear, while the front stabilizer bar became 5 percent stiffer. The rear stabilizer bar has become 41 percent softer, and an additional spring with less force than the main one has been added to ensure driving comfort without compromising dynamic characteristics.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Twelve cylinders and two turbochargers generate a lot of heat in the engine compartment originally designed for the V-8. This explains the full-width, rear-facing vent on the redesigned hood, and also uses a redesigned front bumper framing the grille, which is now 25 percent larger, and larger vents in the redesigned fenders. Other visual changes compared to the regular V8 Vantage include large one-piece side sills extending from the vents on the wings, a new rear bumper with integrated diffuser and central dual exhaust pipes.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The spectacular rear wing, the softly outlined shape of which echoes the shape of the rear wing on the Aston Martin AMR22 F1 car, is designed not only to impress others: it was designed to work with the new front splitter, which creates a downforce of 204 kg at a speed of 321 km/h.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>At first glance, a large V-12 fills the engine compartment of the Vantage. But then we noticed that there is still a gap of just over two centimeters in the front of the car, and this is from an engine that weighs significantly more than the 4.0-liter twin-turbocharged V-8 in a regular Vantage. This fact explains why the front and rear weight distribution has only slightly changed from the ideal 50/50 V8 Vantage to 52/48 V12.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Aston engineers didn\'t just rely on the V-12\'s abundance of power and torque to deliver improved performance over the V-8. Weight reduction measures include switching to 16.1-inch front and 14.2-inch rear carbon-ceramic brakes that remove 23 kilograms of unsprung mass, a stainless steel exhaust system that is 6 kg lighter than a conventional Vantage system, a carbon fiber hood, front fenders, and front and rear bumpers. Lightweight forged alloy wheels are available as an option, which allows you to save another 8 kg.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Thus, despite weighing 1,794 kg, the V12 has a 20 percent better power-to-weight ratio than the lighter (by 215 kg) V8 Vantage F1 Edition, which has so far been the most powerful car in the Vantage lineup.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>V12 engine</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Next to the snarling impact pressing into the seat from the V-8 AMG F1 edition, the V12 engine seems strangely sluggish at first, even despite its higher peak torque (752 Nm vs. 684 Nm) at lower revs — 1800 rpm vs. 2000 rpm.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>This is a perception rather than a reality, reinforced by the different power and torque characteristics of the two engines. V-12, even with turbocharging, like revs: while the torque of the V-8 version of F1 begins to decline after 5000 rpm, and its peak power is at 6000 rpm, V-12, even with turbocharging, retains maximum torque up to 6000 rpm and reaches maximum power at 6500 rpm.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Sometimes you can notice a slight delay in turbocharging if you press hard on the gas below 2000 rpm, but as soon as everything comes into balance, acceleration pushes the pilot back into the seat.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Aston is incredibly fast on any road, it reduces the time and space between turns in a way that only a 700 hp car can do. However, it does not have the sporty rigidity of a ride, like, say, a Porsche 911 GT2 RS. The growl of the V12 has a velvety edge and amazing flexibility to overclocking, even with the suspension in the toughest of the three settings, a kind of Gran Turismo on steroids.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>Riding on the track</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>He\'s also fast on the track, even on his road-optimized tires. Giant carbon-ceramic brakes provide inextinguishable braking power. The front part reacts to the soft steering calmly and confidently, despite the extra weight on the front axle, and the mechanical differential with limited slip deftly directs all this power and torque to the asphalt when the pilot presses the gas.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>There are not many 700 hp rear—wheel drive road cars in which you can confidently turn off the traction and stability control system on the track after just a few laps, but the V12 Vantage is one of them. Yes, it has a lot of power, enough to smoke the rear tires at almost any time convenient for the pilot. But the sensitivity of the throttle and the clarity of feedback through the chassis are such that you can feel exactly where the clutch limits are and modulate the input signals accordingly.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Will the car drift? Sure. Track time exposes the only weak link in the V12 Vantage\'s performance arsenal: an eight-speed automatic transmission. As for automation, the ZF eight—speed gearbox used by Aston Martin is the benchmark, but when the pilot starts pressing the V12 Vantage, the upshifts seem to be lagging, and the downshifts seem clumsy, even in track mode. It\'s enough to drive just a couple of laps to understand: a powerful V12 requires precision and clarity of a dual-clutch transmission.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In total, Aston Martin produces only 333 copies of the V12 Vantage, and each of them has already been sold, despite the price, which starts at about $ 300,000.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->', 'Aston Martin V12 Vantage 2023 Test Drive', 'By the end of this decade, the 5.2-liter twin-turbocharged Aston Martin V-12 engine, originally installed in 2016 under the hood of the DB11 coupe, will go down in the history books as the most \"strangled\" by ever-increasing emissions standards and fuel consumption restrictions. But in the Aston Martin V12 Vantage of 2023, the engine has not become weaker, its nature is raging, turning an interesting entry-level sports car into a sparkling supercar', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'aston-martin-v12-vantage-2023-test-drive', '', '', '2022-10-04 22:19:02', '2022-10-04 19:19:02', '', 0, 'http://wordpress-carbook-training.ru/?p=612', 0, 'post', '', 0),
