(615, 2, '2022-10-04 22:24:23', '2022-10-04 19:24:23', '<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>This is the Aston Martin Victor — a supercar created according to an individual project of a private customer, implemented by the own engineering division of the British firm Q by Aston Martin.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Victor pays homage to the classic Aston Martin V8 Vantage of the 1970s and 1980s, and it takes its name from the company\'s then chief executive Victor Gauntlett, under whose leadership the Aston Martin brand flourished again, between 1980 and 1991.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Gauntlett oversaw the second half of the production cycle of the original V8 Vantage and was responsible for negotiating the filming of James Bond in an Aston Martin car for the 1987 film, which featured a specially modified V8 Vantage.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Victor began life as an updated carbon fiber monocoque from the One-77, to which Aston Martin added a number of retro-styled carbon fiber body panels – all of them were designed with hydrodynamic testing of surfaces in mind to maximize downforce.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>According to Aston Martin engineers, at a speed of 160 km/ h, Victor creates 842 Nm of downforce, which is 300 Nm more than the Vantage GT4 already ready for racing.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Like the classic V8 Vantage, the Victor has a flat nose with an aggressive splitter and a square rear with a ducktail spoiler. A similarly shaped radiator grille at the front, as well as a set of round headlights and a Pentland green paint finish, which is similar to the Buckinghamshire green paint as on the original car.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Inside, the custom-made supercar seats and dashboard are trimmed with Conker Bridge leather, and the ceiling upholstery and door posts are made of cashmere. Solid walnut is used for the decoration of the gearshift knob and in the interior trim, and the Victor steering wheel is a redesigned version of the motorsport unit installed on the Vulcan.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Once the Victor\'s platform and aerodynamics were finalized, Aston Martin added many chassis components from the track-only Vulcan, including its internal springs and shock absorbers, central locking hubs and a six-piston carbon-ceramic Brembo braking system.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>All the power is generated by an atmospheric 7.3-liter V12, which produces a staggering 836 hp and 821 Nm of torque. The supercar has rear-wheel drive via a six-speed manual transmission. Thus, the Victor is the most powerful manual sports car ever built by Aston Martin.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->', 'Aston Martin Victor — the most powerful supercar to order', 'This is the Aston Martin Victor — a supercar created according to an individual project of a private customer, implemented by the own engineering division of the British firm Q by Aston Martin.', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'aston-martin-victor-the-most-powerful-supercar-to-order', '', '', '2022-10-04 22:24:23', '2022-10-04 19:24:23', '', 0, 'http://wordpress-carbook-training.ru/?p=615', 0, 'post', '', 0),
