press-carbook-training.ru/?p=620', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(621, 2, '2022-10-04 22:40:50', '2022-10-04 19:40:50', '<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The electric Q4 E-Tron and its sloping roof counterpart, the Q4 E-Tron Sportback, are the most important models for Audi. No automaker in the world offers as many electric vehicles as an auto giant with four rings in its logo. But where the E-Tron SUV, E-Tron Sportback and E-Tron GT served as convincing proof of Audi\'s electric concept, the Q4\'s starting price of $49,995 suggests that Audi will rely on this model to achieve its goal - a complete transition to electric traction in a five—year period.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>To succeed, the 2023 Audi Q4 E-Tron lineup must ensure a smooth transition for buyers of luxury SUVs with internal combustion engines, as well as build quality, attractive design and driving experience that Audi can be proud of. We would like to say that all the tasks have been completed in general.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>About the car</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The Q4 E-Tron and Q4 E-Tron Sportback are the first Audi electric cars built on the Volkswagen Group\'s MEB platform, and can be perceived as luxury versions of the Volkswagen ID4.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>As the name suggests, the Q4 is located in size between the smallest Audi Q3 SUV and the Q5 sales leader. Its wheelbase is closer to the latter, and the interior seems more spacious than its dimensions suggest. As with the Audi Q5 Sportback, the Q4 Sportback has a sloping roof, but is mechanically identical to its regular counterpart.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The transmission options are exactly the same as in the ID4, minus the additional battery of a smaller capacity. Buyers can choose the Q4 40 with one 201-horsepower rear engine or add a 295 hp front engine and all-wheel drive to the Q4 50. The Sportback can only be purchased with a four-wheel drive transmission that can accelerate from a standstill to 100 km/h in 5.8 seconds.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>All models power their engines from an 82.0 kW/h battery. Audi claims a power reserve of 426 km for the single—engine version of the RWD and 389 km for the AWD Q4s - the Sportback has a slight aerodynamic advantage. The maximum charging power is 150 kW. According to Audi, this is enough for 5-80 percent charging in 36 minutes on a high-speed 150 kW DC charger.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Manufacturability? Q4 has it. Audi\'s digital instrument cluster is included as standard, and for 2023, a new 11.6-inch touchscreen infotainment system is included, which will replace the 10.1-inch system installed in the limited edition 2022 models. Prestige models with all-wheel drive are equipped with a smart display with navigation in augmented reality. A charged Q4 E-Tron Sportback Prestige with metal paint, Convenience and Black Optics Plus packages, as well as an additional towing device (AWD Q4 designed for 1200 kg) costs $ 70,090.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>Are there any differences?</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Approaching the Q4, little can be noted, except for a small E-Tron badge on the hatch and a filled front grille, which identify the new model as an electric car. This is part of Audi\'s strategy to facilitate the transition to electrification for potential customers who might otherwise not want to buy an electric car.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The Q4 doesn\'t look particularly elegant — it just looks like another Audi. Small details such as the Audi Easter egg logo in each taillight, the industry\'s first customizable daytime running lights and the E-Tron logo applied to the rear bumper are convincingly excellent.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>We\'ll share our thoughts on the interior in the upcoming interior review, but if you\'ve been in any Audi recently, the Q4 interior is what you\'d expect, and it\'s much more comfortable than the ID4. The infotainment system is responsive and well thought out, the materials look high quality, and, with the exception of some cheap plastic parts, the fit and finish are excellent. There is also a lot of space in the back, but not for 180-centimeter passengers on the Sportback version.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>On the road</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>As for the drive, the Q4 electric transmission is really good. The instantaneous power supply provides a push from the spot when the gas pedal is pressed, but at the same time provides a strong, soft flow of power at speed for maximum passenger comfort. The transmission soothes newcomers to driving an electric car, creating the feeling of driving a car with an incredibly smooth gasoline engine.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Audi navigation is one of the few factory systems worth using. It has simple input, clear instructions and high-quality satellite images on the infotainment screen and digital instrument cluster. Although we don\'t like the adaptive cruise system controls located on a short leg behind the lower left quadrant of the steering wheel, the system brakes and accelerates naturally without failures.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The rest of the test drive made the Q4 E-Tron stumble. Audi equips its new electric SUV with a progressive steering gear ratio, which is designed to provide maneuverability with minimal effort with full locking when parking, but faster deviation on the highway and less shuffling of hands when driving on a winding road.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In the real world, the same steering effort resulting in different turning angles seems unnatural and difficult to predict. We found ourselves constantly making adjustments in the middle of a turn, and although progressive steering successfully fulfills its mission of split personality, it sounds better on paper than in practice.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Steering is not the only factor that needs attention. The brake pedal is compressed by a couple of centimeters before the driver feels the beginning of braking. After pressing the pedal, the brakes are not felt, but they are easy to adjust for a smooth stop at low speeds. However, we encountered situations that required sudden braking, and found that we needed to put in more effort than we initially thought.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Audi handles regenerative braking differently than some automakers. There is no single-pedal driving mode, and even the highest regeneration setting requires frequent use of an unintuitive brake pedal. By default, the Q4 E-Tron stops when the accelerator pedal is released, and one or three clicks on the left steering wheel handle will add more braking gain in recovery mode. Unlike any other electric car we have driven, regeneration resets when the right pedal is pressed, if the driver is not in dynamic mode. Audi insists that the system knows which regenerative braking force to use, but we would like the Q4 to provide the ability to drive properly with one pedal.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The Q4 suspension setup is also far from ideal. We know that Audi understands how to adjust the suspension, and the new A3 is a perfect example of a comfortable, but reliable and well—controlled ride quality, but the Q4 feels sprung and insufficiently cushioned. We experienced minor but constant head bumps, which would have been more unpleasant if the seat had not been so comfortable and had not had such good upholstery.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>We hoped that a confident ride would pay off with handling, but instead the Q4 shows significant body roll in turns, secondary movements after acceleration, as well as tilt and dive during acceleration and braking. An electric SUV also wants to spin when trying to brake in the middle of a turn — this is clearly not what we would like from a crossover.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In addition to adaptive cruise, the Q4 also lacks driver assistants. While Cadillac makes the hands-free Super Cruise control standard for every Lyriq, and Genesis includes excellent lane centering and autonomous lane switching with all GV60, the Q4 lane control system (if you choose the $6,600 premium package) is nothing more than a decent lane—keeping assistance system., which can switch from one lane to another.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>Our opinion</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Audi managed to create an electric car for the masses, which will facilitate the transition from cars with internal combustion engines to electric cars. No learning curve, no giant touchscreen controlling everything, no 2040 concept car design. The Q4 E-Tron has the build quality and refined, restrained design that we\'ve come to expect from Audi. If you need a semi-affordable German luxury SUV, which, it turns out, can be electric, buy yourself a Q4.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Where Audi has failed is in creating a competitive electric car. Hyundai Ioniq 5, Kia EV6 and Genesis GV60 provide a larger power reserve, faster charging and excellent driving experience. Cadillac Lyriq is distinguished by an elegant, attractive design and an excellent driver assistance system, as well as an increased driving range, additional interior space and improved driving characteristics. Audi is more than capable of creating great cars, but for us the Q4 is not quite ready yet, compared to its main competitor.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->', 'Audi Q4 E-Tron 2023 Test Drive: Audi\'s cheapest electric car could be better', 'The electric Q4 E-Tron and its sloping roof counterpart, the Q4 E-Tron Sportback, are the most important models for Audi. No automaker in the world offers as many electric vehicles as an auto giant with four rings in its logo. But where the E-Tron SUV, E-Tron Sportback and E-Tron GT', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'audi-q4-e-tron-2023-test-drive-audis-cheapest-electric-car-could-be-better', '', '', '2022-10-04 22:40:50', '2022-10-04 19:40:50', '', 0, 'http://wordpress-carbook-training.ru/?p=621', 0, 'post', '', 0),
