 the upcoming interior review, but if you\'ve been in any Audi recently, the Q4 interior is what you\'d expect, and it\'s much more comfortable than the ID4. The infotainment system is responsive and well thought out, the materials look high quality, and, with the exception of some cheap plastic parts, the fit and finish are excellent. There is also a lot of space in the back, but not for 180-centimeter passengers on the Sportback version.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>On the road</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>As for the drive, the Q4 electric transmission is really good. The instantaneous power supply provides a push from the spot when the gas pedal is pressed, but at the same time provides a strong, soft flow of power at speed for maximum passenger comfort. The transmission soothes newcomers to driving an electric car, creating the feeling of driving a car with an incredibly smooth gasoline engine.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Audi navigation is one of the few factory systems worth using. It has simple input, clear instructions and high-quality satellite images on the infotainment screen and digital instrument cluster. Although we don\'t like the adaptive cruise system controls located on a short leg behind the lower left quadrant of the steering wheel, the system brakes and accelerates naturally without failures.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The rest of the test drive made the Q4 E-Tron stumble. Audi equips its new electric SUV with a progressive steering gear ratio, which is designed to provide maneuverability with minimal effort with full locking when parking, but faster deviation on the highway and less shuffling of hands when driving on a winding road.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In the real world, the same steering effort resulting in different turning angles seems unnatural and difficult to predict. We found ourselves constantly making adjustments in the middle of a turn, and although progressive steering successfully fulfills its mission of split personality, it sounds better on paper than in practice.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Steering is not the only factor that needs attention. The brake pedal is compressed by a couple of centimeters before the driver feels the beginning of braking. After pressing the pedal, the brakes are not felt, but they are easy to adjust for a smooth stop at low speeds. However, we encountered situations that required sudden braking, and found that we needed to put in more effort than we initially thought.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Audi handles regenerative braking differently than some automakers. There is no single-pedal driving mode, and even the highest regeneration setting requires frequent use of an unintuitive brake pedal. By default, the Q4 E-Tron stops when the accelerator pedal is released, and one or three clicks on the left steering wheel handle will add more braking gain in recovery mode. Unlike any other electric car we have driven, regeneration resets when the right pedal is pressed, if the driver is not in dynamic mode. Audi insists that the system knows which regenerative braking force to use, but we would like the Q4 to provide the ability to drive properly with one pedal.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The Q4 suspension setup is also far from ideal. We know that Audi understands how to adjust the suspension, and the new A3 is a perfect example of a comfortable, but reliable and well—controlled ride quality, but the Q4 feels sprung and insufficiently cushioned. We experienced minor but constant head bumps, which would have been more unpleasant if the seat had not been so comfortable and had not had such good upholstery.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>We hoped that a confident ride would pay off with handling, but instead the Q4 shows significant body roll in turns, secondary movements after acceleration, as well as tilt and dive during acceleration and braking. An electric SUV also wants to spin when trying to brake in the middle of a turn — this is clearly not what we would like from a crossover.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In addition to adaptive cruise, the Q4 also lacks driver assistants. While Cadillac makes the hands-free Super Cruise control standard for every Lyriq, and Genesis includes excellent lane centering and autonomous lane switching with all GV60, the Q4 lane control system (if you choose the $6,600 premium package) is nothing more than a decent lane—keeping assistance system., which can switch from one lane to another.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>Our opinion</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Audi managed to create an electric car for the masses, which will facilitate the transition from cars with internal combustion engines to electric cars. No learning curve, no giant touchscreen controlling everything, no 2040 concept car design. The Q4 E-Tron has the build quality and refined, restrained design that we\'ve come to expect from Audi. If you need a semi-affordable German luxury SUV, which, it turns out, can be electric, buy yourself a Q4.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Where Audi has failed is in creating a competitive electric car. Hyundai Ioniq 5, Kia EV6 and Genesis GV60 provide a larger power reserve, faster charging and excellent driving experience. Cadillac Lyriq is distinguished by an elegant, attractive design and an excellent driver assistance system, as well as an increased driving range, additional interior space and improved driving characteristics. Audi is more than capable of creating great cars, but for us the Q4 is not quite ready yet, compared to its main competitor.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->', 'Audi Q4 E-Tron 2023 Test Drive: Audi\'s cheapest electric car could be better', 'The electric Q4 E-Tron and its sloping roof counterpart, the Q4 E-Tron Sportback, are the most important models for Audi. No automaker in the world offers as many electric vehicles as an auto giant with four rings in its logo. But where the E-Tron SUV, E-Tron Sportback and E-Tron GT', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '621-revision-v1', '', '', '2022-10-04 22:40:50', '2022-10-04 19:40:50', '', 621, 'http://wordpress-carbook-training.ru/?p=623', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(624, 2, '2022-11-19 16:03:57', '2022-11-19 13:03:57', '<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>This fast station wagon is obviously one of Audi\'s most sophisticated products. Since RS2, four rings from Ingolstadt have become synonymous with practicality. BMW recently announced its G81 M3 Touring loaded station wagon, which made a lot of noise among enthusiasts of fast station wagons. Moreover, BMW has xDrive, so it will be difficult for Audi to claim the role of all-wheel drive king. The new RC4 Competition looks attractive in this gray color on the new 20-inch alloy wheels with Y-shaped spokes, behind which bright red brake calipers hide. The new front splitter, front air intakes, rear diffuser and exterior mirrors are finished with brushed carbon fiber.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The same goes for the interior, which has been improved and now includes almost all the options you could get in a regular RS 4, as well as some bespoke touches to make it stand out, such as red stitching in different places, alcantara steering, a great B&amp;O audio system and comfortable bucket seats.<br>Under the hood is a 2.9-liter V6 engine with dual turbocharging, which does not differ from the usual RS4. The power remained at the same level: 444 hp and 442 Nm of torque. The sound isn\'t as bombastic as one would expect given the size of the pipes, but it adds a little more bass and rumble when you press the pedal.<br>The gearbox received software settings for faster switching and more aggressive perception of changes, which helped to reduce the acceleration time to 100 km / h by 0.2 seconds, and make up 3.9 seconds. Meanwhile, the top speed has been increased by 40 km per hour compared to the standard RS4, to 290 km per hour. While the changes to the transmission were relatively minor, a lot of work was put into the chassis. The main elements, of course, are the new coilovers with three-way shock absorbers, manually adjustable…</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->', 'Review of the improved Audi RS4 Competition 2022', 'This fast station wagon is obviously one of Audi\'s most sophisticated products. Since RS2, four rings from Ingolstadt have become synonymous with practicality. BMW recently announced its', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'review-of-the-improved-audi-rs4-competition-2022', '', '', '2022-11-19 16:03:57', '2022-11-19 13:03:57', '', 0, 'http://wordpress-carbook-training.ru/?p=624', 0, 'post', '', 0),
