(655, 2, '2022-11-19 18:42:53', '2022-11-19 15:42:53', '<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The war of horsepower is over. The war for controllability continues. Cars like the Audi RS5 coupe and sportback with the Competition Plus package, as well as the stunning new GT3 RS from Porsche ― the cars we\'ve been driving for just a few weeks suggest that a paradigm shift is coming in the high-performance car segment.<br>In the era of modern technology these days, when \"anyone\" can build an electric car with a capacity of 2000 horsepower, which will start with insane acceleration, develop internal combustion engines that give out more and more power, providing a slight improvement in acceleration time and maximum speed, is a very thankless occupation.<br>But what about creating a road car chassis with hardware and software that will allow enthusiasts and enthusiastic racers to be whole seconds faster on the race track than their rivals? This is a more complex skill set. Perhaps this explains the growing attention of brands seeking to improve the performance of their flagships to chassis tuning, because it equally ensures driving accuracy and driver joy.<br>The newest harbinger of this trend is the Lamborghini Urus Performante of 2023, which is due to appear before the end of the year and will cost from $260,676.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>Performance is more than acceleration on a straight</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>4.0-liter Urus Performante twin-turbocharged V-8 engine develops only 15 horsepower more than a conventional Urus powerplant, at the same torque. The fact that it is three tenths of a second faster in acceleration to 100 km/h and 1.3 seconds faster to 200 km/h than a regular Urus is more due to a slight weight reduction, improved grip, faster and smoother gear shifting and improved aerodynamics.<br>The whole point of the Urus Performante is not how much faster it is than a regular Urus in a straight line, but how much faster it goes through turns.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:quote -->\n<blockquote class=\"wp-block-quote\"><!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>\"The mission was to make this car the best in its segment, in how the car engages the driver in the driving process.\"<br>Lamborghini Technical Director Reuven Mohr</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph --></blockquote>\n<!-- /wp:quote -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>That\'s why Lamborghini spent most of its budget on engineering the Urus Performante chassis. The first step was to abandon the height-adjustable air suspension in a conventional Urus in favor of steel springs and magnetorheological shock absorbers, the compression and recoil speed of which could be made softer or stiffer depending on the selected driving mode.<br>Why? The air suspension uses rubber and compressed air, so the suspension behavior is nonlinear. With steel springs, predictable, linear behavior is always obtained. This means that the shock absorbers can be precisely tuned for excellent body control provided by steel springs, and the car can be equipped with tires that respond much faster to side impacts and loads.<br>There are no air suspension racing cars on the planet, because from a dynamic point of view, this is the wrong choice. If we talk about the best interaction of the car with the driver from a sporting point of view, then you can\'t do without a steel suspension. The Urus Performante with steel springs crouched 1.5 centimeters lower than the Urus with air suspension, in the default state, and its track was expanded by 1 centimeter. The active roll protection system was carried over from the standard Urus, but was configured in such a way as to take advantage of a more precise suspension on steel springs, as well as a steering system on the rear wheels and torque control.<br>The massive 17.3-inch front and 14.6-inch rear carbon-ceramic brakes have not changed, but the standard 22-inch wheels of the Urus Performante can be equipped with a new, more tenacious high—performance rubber Pirelli P Zero Trofeo R - 285/40 front and 325/35 rear, which was specially designed for this car and is available as an option. Keen-eyed enthusiasts will be able to recognize fans of fast driving by the additional 23-inch Urus Performantes wheels: they do not come with Trofeo R tires.<br>As before, the 4.0-liter twin-turbocharged V-8 engine, which produces 656 hp at 6000 rpm and 850 Nm of torque at 2300-4500 rpm, is driven by an eight-speed automatic transmission. However, the transmission has been reprogrammed to be smoother and more responsive, especially in manual mode. The torque is transmitted to all four wheels via the Torsen center differential, which has been configured to transmit more torque to the rear axle during acceleration.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>More aggressive appearance</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Lamborghini\'s chief designer Mitya Borkert has changed the appearance of the Urus Performante, but not just to make the gloomy Sant\'Agata Bolognese super-SUV look even more like Darth Vader in a bad mood. The redesigned front bumper is equipped with an enlarged splitter and new air intakes to improve cooling and create an air curtain over the front wheels. Ventilation holes in the redesigned hood help to reduce the air pressure in the engine compartment. The new rear bumper has vents behind the rear wheels and a new diffuser layout between the quad-core exhaust pipes of the Bazooka caliber, and the rear wing extends from the roof over the backlight.<br>The new Urus Performante hood is made of carbon fiber as part of a weight reduction program that includes a titanium exhaust pipe, lightweight interior trim, forged alloy wheels and an additional carbon fiber roof. Lamborghini can paint a car in almost any shade.<br>Black alcantara interior trim with a new hexagonal stitching on the seats is included as standard, and leather is offered as an option. Other options include extending the Performante trim on the doors, roof and seatback trim, as well as brushed carbon fiber and red door handles.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>What does it all come down to?</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Hardware and software changes to the chassis provide a 5 percent improvement in both steering response and grip level, styling changes improve aerodynamic efficiency by 10 percent and increase the downforce of the rear axle by 38 percent, and lightweight components reduce the total weight by 47 kilograms. This may not seem like very big numbers. But the sum total is a Lamborghini Urus, which is really much more driver-oriented, as we discovered on the fast 5-kilometer Vallelunga circuit, 30 kilometers north of Rome.<br>On low- and medium-speed turns in Vallelunga, where a regular Urus requires some patience, the Urus Performante rushes into turns like a hungry shark, especially in Corsa mode, which uses all the capabilities of the transmission and chassis systems of the car.<br>The fast and concise reaction of the front part to the turn is so great that it\'s hard to believe, but the Performante is built on the same VW Group architecture with a front engine and a heavy nose, which also underlies Bentley\'s Bentayga.<br>The Urus can be big and tall and still weigh more than 2,130 kg, but it still behaves almost as playfully as the Impreza WRX on the turns of the Vallelunga. Elsewhere, at higher speeds, the big Lamborghini remains flat and tenacious, even as it overcomes compression in the middle of an intimidating fifth-gear right-hand drive called the Curve Grande. The absence of a roll, dive, squat or diagonal step is absolutely amazing.<br>We didn\'t have the opportunity to ride the Urus Performante on the rough roads around the circuit, but even on the track you can see that in Corsa mode the suspension seems very stiff, perhaps too stiff for normal roads. In a car configured in normal Strada mode, as in a regular Urus, a long wheelbase and a wide track will soften the main driving movements, and comfortable, supportive seats will soften most of the secondary vibrations.<br>New to the Urus Performante is the rally mode, which specifically adjusts the chassis so as to allow the big Lambo to dance on the gravel road like a rally racer. Among other things, the shock absorption and compression ratio of the shock absorbers are softened more than when adjusting the Strada, which allows the Performante to move much more on its springs, initiating a reaction to turns and improving grip on loose and uneven surfaces.<br>Accustomed to the Subaru Impreza\'s side roll on gravel or snow, they will notice a slight additional movement of the rear of the Urus Performante, which will turn the car around more than they would like. This is steering on the rear wheels and torque control. According to Mora, it is designed to help novice drivers, who usually continue to turn the steering wheel in turns, at the moment of the start of the skid, instead of opening the steering when the power is turned on.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:quote -->\n<blockquote class=\"wp-block-quote\"><!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>If the car understands that it wants to start skidding, then you just need to have the courage and step on the gas. The rest depends on the car. If you are a professional driver and you have been taught to drift in cars without control systems, then you will have to rethink it a little</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph --></blockquote>\n<!-- /wp:quote -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>How fast? It\'s up to you</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Okay, rally mode is a kind of trick, but it doesn\'t detract from the essence that defines the Urus Performante: it may have only 15 more horses under the hood than a regular Urus, but it\'s 3.5 seconds faster on the Vallelunga lap. Approximately 1.5 seconds of this time falls on the Trofeo R tires. The rest is due to the improvement of the hardware and software of the chassis.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->', 'Lamborghini Urus Performance 2023 Test Drive', 'The war of horsepower is over. The war for controllability continues. Cars like the Audi RS5 coupe and sportback with the Competition Plus package, as well as the stunning new GT3 RS from Porsche ― the ', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'lamborghini-urus-performance-2023-test-drive', '', '', '2022-11-19 18:46:51', '2022-11-19 15:46:51', '', 0, 'http://wordpress-carbook-training.ru/?p=655', 0, 'post', '', 0),
