(661, 2, '2022-11-19 18:51:57', '2022-11-19 15:51:57', '<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>For more than 30 years of history, the legendary supercar has not lost anything in terms of its influence</strong><br>Lamborghini Countach VIN ZA9C005A0KLA12085 is the last car built at the Sant\'Agata Bolognese factory. Once, when I was a kid, I saw an orange Countach parked on a gray cobblestone street in Old Montreal. My father was patient enough to let me stand with my jaw on the same cobblestones, as stunned as a 9-year-old can be. Has it been 10 minutes, 20, half an hour? I don\'t know.<br>Even though it was a long time ago, the memories helped me think, my career, my life to this day. How can such a form exist, let alone a machine? Moreover, how could I stand next to this message of an alien civilization? Most importantly, how do I get behind the wheel? Because suddenly, right at that place and at that moment, I had a pretty clear idea of what I wanted to do in my life. Whoever I become, cars like this Lamborghini in the color Arancio Livrea should be present in my life.<br>Lamborghini in 1987 was completely defined by a powerful wedge-shaped supercar. Sorry, Jalpa fans, but you know it\'s true. I\'ve seen this model at least 50 times. And this segment is the single greatest work of automotive journalism.<br>Imagine that you have been a Countach fan all your life and decades later you are leaving the factory behind the wheel of the last car in history. I was in shock. Could this be real? I should probably omit the details about the rain, the bad electric seats (later developed by Countach), which even with a height of only 165 cm, my head rested against the ceiling, as well as the lack of power steering and at least three turns with locking, the clutch pedal with a 35-kilogram effort., constantly fogged windshield, lack of noticeable brakes — in fact, all the usual Countach sores. I didn\'t give a damn about this list of problems, not even one iota. I smiled for four hours in a row until I had to take the car back.<br>By 1990, Countach was 17 years old. The 25th anniversary model was released two years earlier to celebrate the founding of the company, and, according to rumors, the successor to Countach, Diablo, was to debut in the same year. However, for a variety of reasons, for example, due to the fact that its design was rejected by Lee Iacocca, CEO of Chrysler, which owned Lamborghini, the release of the Diablo was postponed for two years.<br>Although I doubt the company knew about it at the time, it had a young superstar designer, one Horacio Pagani. He was tasked with refining an aging supercar for one last campaign. Mechanically identical to the 5000 QV, also known as the Quattrovalvole, the 449-horsepower 5.2-liter four-chamber 48-valve V-12 was now powered through larger, efficient new air intakes. The rear brakes were equipped with air ducts. Did Pagani make the model dedicated to the 25th anniversary too similar to the Ferrari Testarossa? Perhaps. However, it doesn\'t matter, since this car was a bestseller among all the Counties.<br>Now here\'s the thing: I\'ve driven a few Countaches. These are not very good cars. They are slower than you can imagine, they are clumsy, difficult to see and uncomfortable, the latter is especially pronounced if it is hot outside. And yet, for some reason, the Countach remains my favorite supercar. However, I know about other cars in the Lamborghini museum at the factory: Miura, Espada, LM002, Diablo GT, Reventón, Sesto Elemento and Veneno, and these are just some of those that I would be interested in driving. But Lamborghini exists today thanks to Countach.<br>Of course, Miura is very beautiful, and LM002 is Rambo Lambo, and Diablo is rad, and all that. But it was the madness of Countach, its improbability, its outrage, its dissimilarity, the extreme of its design, its outright banditry that attracted crowds of fans to it. It was the Countach and the spirit of Countach in general that caused the purchase of Lamborghini by the Chrysler auto giant, and that\'s why VW did the same about ten years later. What does this spirit entail? Just a promise that the world would be a less interesting place if Lamborghini wasn\'t around.<br>So, despite the fact that I had other options for choosing a retro car, it was not difficult for me to choose the latest Countach. Like Safer 35 years ago, I drove out of the factory gates on a masterpiece of Marcello Gandini design. Except that I will be driving, and not the legendary Lamborghini test pilot Valentino Balboni.<br>A few years ago I was stuck in a terrible traffic jam in Los Angeles with Balboni inside Gallardo LP 550-2 Valentino Balboni Edition. We had no reason to talk about his eponymous car, but I still asked him what he experienced when he first saw the Countach. \"Ah, Countach!\" he said. \"Impossible! No one believed it was a car.<br>He explained that when the prototype flew along the roads along the vineyards of Sant\'Agata many years ago, it looked like a spaceship because nothing on earth looked like it. \"Power! Steering! Manageability! Brakes…\" he paused, then shrugged and said, \"Well, not so much brakes,\" making the sign of the cross. But his smile showed that my question had awakened nostalgic feelings in him.<br>Apparently, there is only one road in the province of Modena (Italy), which, according to local manufacturers, is worth driving, and now I took Pagani, Ferrari and the last Countach to \"take photos\". This is a beautiful country road that goes uphill. There is a minimal number of cars here, and you can have a lot of fun: I almost crashed a Pagani Huayra there, because I tried to make an unfinished maneuver.<br>Well, I almost slammed the last Countach too, because it was pouring rain, and I couldn\'t see anything because of it. The photographer I was transporting from place to place kept laughing at the absurdity of the situation. The only way I could see through the windshield was for the photographer to lean forward and wipe the glass with a rag. As soon as he got out of the car, I was sprayed with a hose. Everything you have ever read about how pathetic and weak the Countach ventilation, ventilation and air conditioning system is is completely true.<br>The photos, however, as you can see, are outstanding. The silver color looks dull on a Lamborghini, but on wet asphalt against the background of bright Italian greenery it looks spectacular. Looking at these pictures now, it\'s easy to understand what it cost to break through adverse weather conditions. None of that mattered, except for the part when I drove a Lamborghini Countach around Italy. The smile I mentioned earlier was invincible: I even smiled when I realized that I needed to take off my shoes to get behind the wheel, and when it became known by experience that the Countach is not completely waterproof, as evidenced by my wet socks. None of that mattered.<br>The car, despite all its quirks, is perfect. Completely imperfect, completely ridiculous, completely alien. But still perfect. These days we spend so much time worrying about measurements — fractions of a second here, how much power an engine produces there. I\'ve been told that people won\'t consider buying a certain car because it doesn\'t have Apple CarPlay. CarPlay? Countach doesn\'t have a trunk!<br>Look at the Porsche 911 GT3 RS that will be released soon. It looks extreme, but everything is done for performance reasons. And on Countach? The famous rear wing actually slows down the car. Believe it or not, but despite its shortcomings, and perhaps because of them, the last Countach in history is just a joy on wheels.<br>This Countach, like all the others, is an attitude, an attitude, a monument to what could have been and really should be. I just get happier with him than without him. Are cars an art? Will they ever be able to become a real art? Few can, and the Countach is one of the rare cars that will bring its owner as much joy, bolted to the wall as parked in the garage. The car is just amazing. Remember, the name comes from the word contacc, a Piedmontese interjection used when a person is shocked and surprised.<br>Maybe you think the car and its legend are too exaggerated after so many years. But really, after all this time, after all the cars, supercars and hypercars that I have driven in my career, there is only one that takes me back to the origins of my hobby. Only one that brings me back to my a priori love of cars, to undoubtedly simpler and happier times.<br>Of course, today the world is full of wonderful cars, but how many of them make you say \"Wow!\" in the same tone as Countach? Not many, and even fewer cars remain a dream…</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->', 'Behind the wheel of the latest Lamborghini Countach: there is no supercar like it to this day', 'Lamborghini Countach VIN ZA9C005A0KLA12085 is the last car built at the Sant\'Agata Bolognese factory. Once, when I was a kid, I saw an orange Countach parked on a gray cobblestone street in Old Montreal. ', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'behind-the-wheel-of-the-latest-lamborghini-countach-there-is-no-supercar-like-it-to-this-day', '', '', '2022-11-19 18:51:57', '2022-11-19 15:51:57', '', 0, 'http://wordpress-carbook-training.ru/?p=661', 0, 'post', '', 0),
