(664, 2, '2022-11-19 18:57:10', '2022-11-19 15:57:10', '<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Mercedes Jellinek and Karl Benz existed in a different era than Hans Werner Aufrecht and Erhard Melcher, but the Mercedes-AMG SL63 of 2022 is a car that they would all really like. If their lives had crossed, these key characters in the story of the \"Silver Arrow\" would have been happy to ride together in this new sports car with a convertible 2 + 2 — Mercedes and Benz would have chosen seats in the second row, and the fathers of AMG would have ridden in the first.<br>This hypothetical seating arrangement reflects a new attitude towards the updated SL-class. Previous versions of the Sport Leicht were comfortable grand tours that were sent to the AMG training camp from time to time. But for the latest SL63 model, the conversion to AMG was in the first place, and it turned out to be outstanding. The car bristles with a frenzied edge, sacrificing part of its traditional comfort for the sake of dynamism. The result is a roadster that looks more like an AMG than a Mercedes-Benz, and is undoubtedly the most high-performance SL ever.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>Affalterbach Muscles</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>SLS, GT, One, and now SL: the fact that it has joined the ranks of exclusive AMG models underlines the sporting intentions of the new R232 generation model. The entry-level SL43 of the line is also the leader of AMG\'s movement towards electrification, it has a 2.0-liter turbocharged four-cylinder engine improved by Formula 1 technologies. But the 4.0-liter twin-turbocharged V-8 engine of the M177 remains the most attractive and currently the only engine option available for SL AMG models in most European countries. Power 469 hp and 700 Nm of torque in the SL55, which is additionally pumped up to 577 hp and 800 Nm in the SL63 thanks to the addition of larger turbochargers and updated software.<br>The MCT nine—speed automatic transmission (starting with a torque converter) transfers this power to the AMG version with the Mercedes 4Matic all-wheel drive system - a combination never seen before in the SL. These elements combine to provide ferocious starts with incredible ease. By turning on one of the Sport drive modes, you can press two pedals simultaneously, the tachometer shows 3500 rpm against the background of the ominous growl of exhaust gases. Releasing the brake, the torque converter turns off, and the SL63 accelerates to 100 km/h in 3.1 seconds, 160 km/ h in 7.3 seconds and the distance of 400 meters is overcome in 11.3 seconds with a final speed of 199.5 km/h. Acceleration continues to a speed of 320 km/h, accompanied by a distinct roar of AMG all the way.<br>Although there have been more powerful and torque-rich SL models in the past, none of them were faster than the new SL63. The closest thing to acceleration to 100 km/h in our tests was a 3.5-second sprint SL63, equipped with an old 5.5-liter V-8 engine with dual turbocharging and torque of 873 Nm. The previous holder of the SL title at an acceleration of up to 160 km/h and a run of 400 meters was the legendary SL65 Black series, which reached these marks in 7.8 seconds and 11.6 seconds at a speed of 199.3 km/h, respectively. The perfect grip provided by the new SL63 4Matic system is the decisive factor here. However, when moving from a standstill, the gearbox may stutter slightly due to the engagement of the clutch discs. In addition, gear shifting occurs instantly with a convincing push at reduced power, although sometimes inconsistent automatic gear selection makes manual mode preferable for efficient driving.<br>The huge additional carbon-ceramic brakes of the SL63 2022 serve as a worthy counterweight to its frenzied acceleration. The braking distance of 32 meters at 100 km/h is really impressive, although it is not a record for SL or AMG: the SL63 of the previous generation of the R231 series, which we tested, stopped after 31 meters, and the GT Black series did it after an amazing 28. Nevertheless, these brakes seem fantastic. The pedal stroke is short, sensitive and surprisingly progressive, the return stops correspond exactly to the driver\'s contribution — they will suit drivers and racers equally well.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>Manageability</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The body of the new SL, made of aluminum, steel, magnesium and carbon composite, is much better than that of the previous model, withstands twisting and bending forces. This architecture is so powerful that it will be used by the next—generation AMG GT - and even without a roof, the SL63 demonstrates not far gone handling performance from our best car of 2015 — the AMG GT S.<br>On the drift platform, the SL63 demonstrated lateral overload to a skid of an average of 1.03 g. Various tests of the AMG GT S ranged from 1.03 to 1.09 g. The SL63 makes a circle along the trajectory of the eight in 23.6 seconds with an average overload of 0.87 g. That\'s within four tenths of a second of the GT S, and a full second ahead of the SL65 Black Series.<br>In addition to Michelin Pilot Sport 4S tires with a ZR rating of 275/35 at the front and 305/30 at the rear on the 21-inch wheels of our test car, the new equipment is designed to improve the handling of the SL63. The AMG Active Ride Control suspension, which replaces the lateral stability stabilizers with interconnected hydraulic lines, keeps the SL63 highly assembled and affects the ride quality. Gone is the smooth glide that made past SL models perfect. Resolute rigidity takes its place, uncomfortable in the sense that it is livable, but not chic.<br>No matter how unpleasant it may be for Mercedes-Benz traditionalists, the handling of the SL63 will please enthusiasts whose Grand Touring routes are optimized for stable speed. Despite this, the SL63 cannot be classified as an elite sports car — despite its AMG zeal, Mercedes\' lackluster layer remains. No matter how advanced the chassis is, nothing hides its size or curb weight of 1927 kg. Neither the steering, nor the engine, nor the transmission are so sensitive.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>Part cruiser, part sport</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Despite the wildness, the SL63 is equipped with materials, technologies and amenities that range from dazzling to exquisite. This was reflected in its price, which is significantly higher than before: starting at $180,450, the SL63 tested here was richly equipped with options such as an attractive hyper-ceramic paint worth $1,750, an aerodynamic package worth $2,850, a Burmester audio system worth $4,500 and the aforementioned carbon-ceramic brakes worth $8,950, thanks to which its total cost is $212,585. But even with this huge amount, you can\'t buy a few physical buttons that have eliminated the need to dig through digital menus to find the basic operations, not least the raising and lowering of the folding soft top.<br>Perhaps this is a trifle, since elements such as its ingenious display, stable semi-autonomous assistants and a touch screen with an adjustable tilt combine functionality and ease of operation. There have never been such front seats that are so resolutely supported and so vigorously massaged, blowing warm air around the necks of their passengers. These luxury items meet the expectations of something so majestic in the constellation of three-pointed stars.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->', 'Mercedes-AMG SL63 2022 Test Drive: Fusion reactor', 'Mercedes Jellinek and Karl Benz existed in a different era than Hans Werner Aufrecht and Erhard Melcher, but the Mercedes-AMG SL63 of 2022 is a car that they would all really like. If their lives had crossed, these ', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'mercedes-amg-sl63-2022-test-drive-fusion-reactor', '', '', '2022-11-19 18:57:10', '2022-11-19 15:57:10', '', 0, 'http://wordpress-carbook-training.ru/?p=664', 0, 'post', '', 0),
