1 meters, and the GT Black series did it after an amazing 28. Nevertheless, these brakes seem fantastic. The pedal stroke is short, sensitive and surprisingly progressive, the return stops correspond exactly to the driver\'s contribution — they will suit drivers and racers equally well.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>Manageability</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The body of the new SL, made of aluminum, steel, magnesium and carbon composite, is much better than that of the previous model, withstands twisting and bending forces. This architecture is so powerful that it will be used by the next—generation AMG GT - and even without a roof, the SL63 demonstrates not far gone handling performance from our best car of 2015 — the AMG GT S.<br>On the drift platform, the SL63 demonstrated lateral overload to a skid of an average of 1.03 g. Various tests of the AMG GT S ranged from 1.03 to 1.09 g. The SL63 makes a circle along the trajectory of the eight in 23.6 seconds with an average overload of 0.87 g. That\'s within four tenths of a second of the GT S, and a full second ahead of the SL65 Black Series.<br>In addition to Michelin Pilot Sport 4S tires with a ZR rating of 275/35 at the front and 305/30 at the rear on the 21-inch wheels of our test car, the new equipment is designed to improve the handling of the SL63. The AMG Active Ride Control suspension, which replaces the lateral stability stabilizers with interconnected hydraulic lines, keeps the SL63 highly assembled and affects the ride quality. Gone is the smooth glide that made past SL models perfect. Resolute rigidity takes its place, uncomfortable in the sense that it is livable, but not chic.<br>No matter how unpleasant it may be for Mercedes-Benz traditionalists, the handling of the SL63 will please enthusiasts whose Grand Touring routes are optimized for stable speed. Despite this, the SL63 cannot be classified as an elite sports car — despite its AMG zeal, Mercedes\' lackluster layer remains. No matter how advanced the chassis is, nothing hides its size or curb weight of 1927 kg. Neither the steering, nor the engine, nor the transmission are so sensitive.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>Part cruiser, part sport</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Despite the wildness, the SL63 is equipped with materials, technologies and amenities that range from dazzling to exquisite. This was reflected in its price, which is significantly higher than before: starting at $180,450, the SL63 tested here was richly equipped with options such as an attractive hyper-ceramic paint worth $1,750, an aerodynamic package worth $2,850, a Burmester audio system worth $4,500 and the aforementioned carbon-ceramic brakes worth $8,950, thanks to which its total cost is $212,585. But even with this huge amount, you can\'t buy a few physical buttons that have eliminated the need to dig through digital menus to find the basic operations, not least the raising and lowering of the folding soft top.<br>Perhaps this is a trifle, since elements such as its ingenious display, stable semi-autonomous assistants and a touch screen with an adjustable tilt combine functionality and ease of operation. There have never been such front seats that are so resolutely supported and so vigorously massaged, blowing warm air around the necks of their passengers. These luxury items meet the expectations of something so majestic in the constellation of three-pointed stars.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->', 'Mercedes-AMG SL63 2022 Test Drive: Fusion reactor', 'Mercedes Jellinek and Karl Benz existed in a different era than Hans Werner Aufrecht and Erhard Melcher, but the Mercedes-AMG SL63 of 2022 is a car that they would all really like. If their lives had crossed, these ', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '664-revision-v1', '', '', '2022-11-19 18:57:10', '2022-11-19 15:57:10', '', 664, 'http://wordpress-carbook-training.ru/?p=666', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(667, 2, '2022-11-19 18:59:15', '2022-11-19 15:59:15', '<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>This mutant G-Wagen is known as the P 900 Rocket Edition</strong><br>A lot has changed in the automotive industry over the past decade or so, but the tendency of the German Brabus tuner to turn Mercedes-Benz cars into growling (and usually contradictory) beasts remains unchanged. The tuning studio, apparently, is not interested in subtlety, prudence or power below 500 horses. Given the massive presence of the Mercedes-AMG G63, Brabus had to do something different. The P 900 Rocket version is very different from everything previously \"created\". And this is a pickup truck.<br>By itself, the Mercedes-AMG G 63 does not cause ridicule. Its 577-horsepower 4.0-liter twin-turbocharged V-8 engine accelerates a square SUV from a standstill to 100 km/h in just 4.5 seconds. No matter how impressive these numbers are, they may not be enough for some. Brabus engineers turned the G 63 into an incredibly powerful, wide-bodied street animal, which they called the P 900 Rocket Edition.<br>Our eyes immediately rush to the back of this auto-rocket, and this is because Brabus has completely redesigned this beautiful half of the SUV, turning it into a pickup truck. What\'s the point of having all this power and luxury if they can\'t be practical, right? Body modifications do not end there. A set of carbon fiber body parts not only expands the capabilities of the rocket, but can also reduce the total weight by several tens of kilograms.<br>Of course, we can\'t describe this transformation in detail without telling you what Brabus has put under the hood of this supermobile. Brabus starts by dismantling the standard power plant. The pistons have been replaced with forged assemblies of larger diameter, which are connected to \"balanced, high-performance\" connecting rods. A stoker kit is added, which increases the engine capacity to 4.5 liters. Turbochargers have been upgraded and, finally, the control unit has been reprogrammed. The result is an enlarged V-8, which now produces 900 horsepower and a colossal torque of 1,250 Nm.<br>Brabus didn\'t mention any powertrain updates or any useful information about what towing capability this newly-minted pickup can develop, but we don\'t think Rocket buyers want to tow anything to the lake for the weekend.<br>By the way, if you want to buy a Brabus P 900 Rocket Edition, you need to act quickly. The tuner collected only 10 copies of this \"miracle\". It is unclear whether any of these cars are intended for our market, but we believe that anyone who can afford to buy one of them will find a way to do so.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->', 'Brabus turns Mercedes-AMG G63 into a pickup truck covered with carbon fiber P 900 Rocket Edition', 'A lot has changed in the automotive industry over the past decade or so, but the tendency of the German Brabus tuner to turn Mercedes-Benz cars into growling (and usually contradictory) beasts remains ', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'brabus-turns-mercedes-amg-g63-into-a-pickup-truck-covered-with-carbon-fiber-p-900-rocket-edition', '', '', '2022-11-19 19:12:39', '2022-11-19 16:12:39', '', 0, 'http://wordpress-carbook-training.ru/?p=667', 0, 'post', '', 0),
