(682, 2, '2022-11-19 20:10:22', '2022-11-19 17:10:22', '<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>The Black Ghost certainly looks great, but the quality of the ride spoiled our mood.</strong><br>\"More than any other Rolls-Royce luxury car will offer\" — yes, we are practically promised the best that the automotive industry can offer. There\'s no doubt that the Rolls-Royce Ghost is one of the best sedans you can buy, but the top honors go to its larger counterpart, the Phantom, and driving the new version of the Black Badge 2022 makes us ask an uncomfortable question: is this really the best Rolls-Royce?<br>BB Brief description: Introduced in 2016, it is primarily a stylistic experiment, most notable for its darkened bright finish, in particular the Rolls-Royce branded grille and the Spirit of Ecstasy hood design. The black badge has been an incredible success for Rolls-Royce, and in 2022 Ghost will join Cullinan, Dawn and Wraith in a new form, offering its own package of black badges. For $43,850, the kit includes lightweight wheels, a carbon fiber body and beautiful aluminum inserts in the Bolivar ebony finish, as well as increased power and a more rigid chassis calibration.<br>We love visual effects. The darkened chrome looks just fine, and it becomes clear why someone is even considering a Rolls with an old-fashioned bright finish. Our $519,000 test car was made in two-tone black and charcoal gray, but we think the worn-out motif looks equally good compared to the bright primary colors. Not that it matters what we, the masses, think — Rolls-Royces are usually made to order, painted and completed according to the wishes of their buyers, or \"customers\", as Rolls prefers to call these rich people. These are not the people who buy cars from the showroom.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>Not All Improvements Are Improvements</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Driving dynamics is our specialty, and no matter how dreamy Black Ghost looks, his driving on the roads makes you think. After some time spent behind the wheel, we discovered that adding a \"Black Badge\" does not turn a Ghost into something completely different, and this fact does not seem appropriate for Rolls-Royce, especially when the car costs half a million dollars.<br>Let\'s look at the changes and then talk about how they affect the Ghost driving experience. For the 6.7-liter twin-turbocharged V-12, there is a power boost: the Black Badge models produce 592 horsepower and 664 Nm of torque, which is 29 hp and 37 Nm more than conventional Ghosts (Rolls-Royce now calls them the \"Silver Badge\"). The gearbox is set to shift faster when the throttle is almost fully open. Changes to the chassis include enhanced steering, tighter air suspension settings and roll control, as well as a heavier brake pedal, with reduced travel. By the way, all this is done by changes in the software: the mechanical components are completely identical.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>More Power—But is it Noticeable?</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Let\'s start with the power unit. The ghost with the silver badge is already fast — we accelerated it from a standstill to 100 km/h in 4.2 seconds, and we do not think that the additional power of the car with the black badge will be detected with the naked eye. We estimate that the acceleration may increase by a tenth of a second in our instrumental testing, such a figure can easily be lost with elementary rounding. There is an important marketing ploy: if we have a choice, we will always, always, always take where there is more power (especially when money is not a question for us at all), no matter how much the objective performance changes.<br>As for the faster gearbox shifts, we could barely notice the difference. This is because switching speeds up only when the gas is completely squeezed out, and also because it is very limited to test the Ghost on public roads. In other words, this is not exactly an advantage that can be used on a regular basis.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>Better Brakes And Less Roll…</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The changes in the chassis were much more noticeable. The brakes do have a slightly stronger bite, and yet it is still soft, absolutely not sharp. The steering is noticeably heavier, although it does not cause complaints — the steering of the Ghost of the Silver Badge was light, for control with just one finger, and we welcomed the extra weight in the Black Badge. However, without any changes to the Ghost tires or the physical steering mechanism, the heavier steering highlights the lack of feedback at the Ghost steering wheel with the front wheels.<br>The roll of the body has noticeably decreased, although it is worth noting that for all its weight and the softness of the course as on goose down, the Ghost of the Silver Badge also does not roll much.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>But The problem Is the quality of the ride</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The quality of the ride gave us the greatest uncertainty. The ghost with the black badge still floats like a 70s-era Cadillac. The magic of the Silver Badge Ghost is that it creates the feeling that all roads are paved with glass. A car with a black badge loses the ability to smooth the surface under the tires, and with it the charm of the Rolls-Royce is dulled.<br>All this could be acceptable if it turned the Ghost into something similar to the Bentley Flying Spur, in terms of driving performance, which, frankly, is what we were hoping for. But this is not the case. The ghost with the silver badge is stable and safe on high-speed turns, although it is quite clumsy on smaller, narrower roads. A car with a black badge is nominally better, but it still feels awkward and out of place, as if trying to run in too tight shoes.<br>After driving a few kilometers on a fast and serene \"Ghost of a black badge\", we switched to a car with a silver badge. Lightweight and insulated, its driving characteristics were much more consistent with the car as a whole. This is a tramp, not a runner.<br>Our admittedly relatively minor complaints would be less well-founded if we could turn the tighter suspension settings on and off at will, but that\'s not possible. Rolls-Royce attaches great importance to the fact that it does not have a sports button. \"Your right leg is a sports button,\" the company representatives told us. But that\'s not the case, because nothing you do with the accelerator affects the chassis settings. By choosing a Black badge, the client gets, if not completely rude, then at least inappropriate for a Rolls—Royce ride.<br>Rolls-Royce will provide any shade of color that you can wish for, any skin color, any interior decoration. But if a black badge model is needed, we cannot refuse to change the chassis. It is strange that such a restriction is imposed on customers by a brand that is engaged in providing custom cars to its customers.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->', 'Rolls-Royce Black Badge Ghost2022 Test Drive', '\"More than any other Rolls-Royce luxury car will offer\" — yes, we are practically promised the best that the automotive industry can offer. There\'s no doubt that the Rolls-Royce Ghost is one of the best sedans ', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'rolls-royce-black-badge-ghost2022-test-drive', '', '', '2022-11-19 20:10:22', '2022-11-19 17:10:22', '', 0, 'http://wordpress-carbook-training.ru/?p=682', 0, 'post', '', 0),
