(685, 2, '2022-11-19 20:13:00', '2022-11-19 17:13:00', '<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>For many, Rolls-Royce remains a cult brand built on sophistication, luxury and an inconspicuous but impressive effect from the very presence on the roads. But over the past five years, the British firm has been quietly creating its alter ego in the form of Black Badge cars - \"disruptive\" models designed for those customers who buy classic versions of cars and then turn to tuning studios to improve them or remove chrome plating.<br>Simply put, Rolls would prefer to build a car to an upgraded specification at its Goodwood plant and earn increased margins on it. And Black Badge cars currently account for more than a third of the company\'s sales: on the Cullinan SUV, for example, this share is more than 40 percent. Therefore, Rolls included a version of the \"Black Badge\" in the development of the latest Ghost, and we had the opportunity to ride it on the roads of the UK, but only under the cover of darkness.<br>The reason for the evening test is simple: the car had not yet been officially unveiled when we got behind the wheel, and Rolls reasoned that chasing a Ghost with a Black Badge across British landscapes by moonlight would be as disguised as any on the basis of pasting a special film.<br>So, here\'s what you can get for some 30 million rubles or more, according to all calculations, the price can exceed 40 million rubles if you start choosing different options well.<br>The 6.75-liter V12 Ghost engine was reconfigured to a power of 592 hp and a torque of 900 nm, an increase of 29 hp and 50 nm, respectively, and the ZF eight-speed automatic transmission was recalibrated. There was also a new profile for the flat suspension of the car, more voluminous pneumatic shock absorbers appeared, and the four-wheel steering was also adapted to the changes of the car.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In addition, a new \"Low\" button has appeared on the gear selector leg, which switches the exhaust system to a louder setting, forces the gearbox to change gear ratios twice as fast and provides the entire torque of 900 Nm from just 1600 rpm. In other words, this is as close as Rolls will ever be able to come to a sports mode, and although the company does not give performance indicators here, this car should overtake the acceleration time of a standard Ghost from a standstill to 100 km/h in 4.8 seconds by several tenths of a second.<br>As expected, a lot of new materials and trim options have appeared outside and inside the car. Buyers can choose any color, including a shade from Rolls\' own palette of 44,000 colors, but most buyers will choose what the company calls “the darkest black in the automotive industry,” created from 45 kg of paint.<br>The decisive factor for many Black Badge buyers, apparently, is the extension of the dark theme to the front grille: this element receives an additional chrome electrolyte during the coating process, giving a deeper dark shade, with a layer thickness of a hundredth of the width of a human hair. The Ghost Black Badge also gets custom-made 21-inch wheels that have carbon fiber barrels embedded in them.<br>The cabin, meanwhile, features a unique finish that includes carbon and metal fibers woven into a diamond \"weave,\" and there are subtle differences in processing throughout, from the champagne cooler to the clock. These kind of \"differences\", inside and out, cause a real stir among potential customers and the hand begins to reach for the phone to call the bank.<br>First, we drove the Ghost of the Black Badge on a closed test road, where Rolls encouraged us to use its improved body control and feel the increased relevance of the \"Low\" mode. Of course, he demonstrated impressive maneuverability for a 2.5-ton car, resisting the roll of the body and making rapid changes of direction without much fuss.<br>This is probably also fast: starts in \"low\" mode are comically fast if you keep your foot far enough on the gas pedal to ensure gear shifting at maximum speed (this happens only when the right pedal is pressed to 90% and beyond). The V12 engine certainly has a more noticeable sound, although we\'re still talking about Rolls, so don\'t expect an AMG roar.<br>On the road, it\'s hard to know when there really will be time and place to use this additional breadth of opportunities. Rolls-Royce Black Badge Ghost is perfect, fast, assembled and convenient — a real conqueror of distances in GT mode.<br>Despite all the technical subtleties, we still have a car whose appeal is not to be a dynamic transformation of a Ghost, but rather to become a slightly different edition that opens up an alternative way to use. Rolls may call this approach \"subversive\", but, in truth, we can only talk about an increase in the number of brand customers with their own vision of what a luxury car really is.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->', 'Rolls-Royce Black Badge Ghost 2021 Review', 'For many, Rolls-Royce remains a cult brand built on sophistication, luxury and an inconspicuous but impressive effect from the very presence on the roads. But over the past five years, the British firm has ', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'rolls-royce-black-badge-ghost-2021-review', '', '', '2022-11-19 20:13:00', '2022-11-19 17:13:00', '', 0, 'http://wordpress-carbook-training.ru/?p=685', 0, 'post', '', 0),
