(688, 2, '2022-11-19 20:21:58', '2022-11-19 17:21:58', '<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>While the Phantom remains the most luxurious car, and Cullinan has opened Rolls-Royce to a completely new market, you can still get that unforgettable experience from owning the long-known luxury Rolls—Royce Ghost (Ghost - translated from English).<br>From the way it looks on the road to the comfort and sophistication it offers from the spacious and caring interior, the Ghost has become something of a luxury car model. It has an enviable depth of design and serious attention to detail, and although the owners pay a lot of money for this level of quality, the demand for such cars is only increasing.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>About Rolls Royce Ghost</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>There is a big gap in the market between \"ordinary\" luxury cars like the Mercedes S-Class and the Rolls-Royce Phantom, unsurpassed in size, value and luxury, and this is a gap that the Rolls-Royce Ghost fits neatly into. With a length of 5.5 meters and a width of two meters, there are not many other places on the market that the Ghost fits into, but these dimensions still distinguish the heavy sedan as an entry-level model of the Rolls Royce brand.<br>Now it is a second-generation Ghost, replacing the car that debuted in 2009, and although it does not differ much in concept from its predecessor, the latest car is not based on the BMW platform, but this time on the “luxury architecture” of the aviation aluminum frame, which also forms the basis of the Phantom VIII and the Cullinan SUV. This allowed Rolls-Royce to further advance its luxury technology and the newest Ghost became even more technologically advanced than its predecessor.<br>It delivers the quality you\'d expect from Rolls-Royce: light performance from its BMW V12 twin-turbo engine, driving qualities that rank the car among the best, an equally exceptional level of sophistication and an endless list of options that allow the customer to adapt the car to their every whim. The costs of this are literal costs — the costs of buying and equipping a car, and everything is very expensive.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>Motors, performance and drive</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Exceptional pursuit of light performance and maximum comfort, few cars are more comfortable to travel.<br>With its smooth twin-turbo V12 engine and 8-speed automatic ZF, the ghost has become almost inaudible, and you will not find any blades for controlling the gearbox or driving modes that sharpen the reaction of the car.<br>There is potentially tremendous performance, but a Ghost is a car that rewards its driver more for careful, thoughtful gas pedal presses than for any other driving style. It is stable in turns, despite some body roll, and develops its performance with a slight delay.<br>Impressive driving qualities of the car are provided with the help of suspension elements: front double wishbones, rear multi-link suspension, pneumatic springs and adaptive damping device (shock absorber). The car also has a Rolls-Royce planar suspension system, additional damping devices and Flagbearer technology, which scans the road surface with cameras and adjusts the suspension accordingly.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>Engines, acceleration and maximum speed</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>There is only one engine installed in the Ghost. Its volume of 6.75 liters may seem familiar, but the unit itself is completely unrelated to the \"six and three-quarters of a liter\" used in old Rolls-Royces and Bentleys. It is built by BMW, and is also a twin-turbo V12, not a V8.<br>Rolls-Royce claims a power of 563 hp and a huge torque of 850 Nm, enough to accelerate the Ghost from a standstill to 100 km/h in 4.8 seconds, while the maximum speed is limited to 249 km/ h.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>Fuel consumption and operating costs</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>With a twin-turbo V12 and a 2.5-ton body weight, don\'t expect low operating costs, but few owners are likely to be concerned about little things like the cost of gasoline.<br>Officially, the Ghost in combined mode consumes fuel at the level of 12.5 liters / 100 km.<br>And yet this is rather inappropriate when the Ghost has a base price of 24 million rubles, and most owners simply do not care about the price of fuel, nor the high rates of transport tax, nor the high cost of maintenance.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>Depreciation</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Specific residual value data for the latest generation of Ghost has not yet been published, but customers should be encouraged by the strong performance of the previous model, which retained 62% of its original value after three years of operation.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>Interior, design and technology</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The cabin has a fairly simple design and at the same time is beautifully finished and built, and the entertainment in the cabin extends far beyond the central display of the infotainment system.<br>Inside, the Ghost really stands out. Interestingly, the architecture of the interior and dashboard has not changed much compared to the previous generation Ghost, launched in 2009, inspired by the Phantom of the 2000s, but considering that these cars were difficult to combine in terms of design, fit and finish or comfort, the similarity looks quite logical.<br>However, Rolls-Royce has honed the details a bit by installing fewer buttons than before, while at the same time the infotainment screen (a word that Rolls-Royce itself hardly uses) naturally differs by several steps from its predecessor in terms of quality, graphics and functionality.<br>However, in general, the interior of the Ghost is very individual, with endless variations of materials and trim elements that make each car a little different from its counterparts — plus details such as the starlight headliner and doors that close almost effortlessly separating it from any other luxury car.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>Satellite navigation, stereo and infotainment system</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Somewhere deep in the software of the Ghost infotainment complex there will be a bare skeleton from BMW\'s iDrive, but with different graphics, and controlled by a handmade central disk. As for the entertainment in the back seat… well, it depends on what you put in the extra refrigerator.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>Practicality, comfort and luggage space</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Huge even in a standard wheelbase, the Ghost is a great place to travel no matter where you sit<br>Practicality is a vague term for a car like a Ghost. It is unlikely to include the ability to put furniture in the trunk or have corrugated surfaces like a Land Rover, but it needs to accommodate passengers more comfortably than on any other car and take luggage of reasonable volumes to meet the needs of the owner.<br>The ghost achieves its goals, as expected. The smallest Rolls-Royce is still more majestic than almost any other luxury car for sale, and attracts passengers like few cars, except for other Rolls-Royce models. It is quiet, incredibly smooth to drive and can be equipped with countless amenities for life.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>Size</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Available in both conventional and extended wheelbase versions, even the standard Ghost is a large beast, stretching 5545 mm in length, 1979mm in width and 1552mm in height, with a wheelbase of 3295 mm.<br>The model with an extended wheelbase increases this figure to 3465 mm, in turn increasing the length of the car itself by 5715 mm — only 47 mm less than the standard Phantom wheelbase. The Ghost also weighs 2553 kg in the standard form and 2599 kg in the extended model.<br>To be honest, from the point of view of the comfort level of the passengers of the \"ghost\", you are unlikely to be dissatisfied. No seat lacks space, even in the shorter of the two body options.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>Trunk</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>You won\'t be able to carry cabinets on it, but for ordinary luggage, the 507-liter Ghost space should be enough. However, it really shrinks if you check the box for the refrigerator option “central refrigerator\".</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>Reliability and safety</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Unsurprisingly, no one has crashed a Ghost on a crash test yet, but the safety should still be excellent, and the service and warranty coverage comprehensive.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>Service</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>There are no defined maintenance intervals for the Ghost, and condition-based maintenance means that the car itself controls various criteria. Rolls-Royce also offers owners two-, three- and five-year service packages after the four-year warranty period.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->', 'Rolls Royce Ghost — Luxury Car review', 'While the Phantom remains the most luxurious car, and Cullinan has opened Rolls-Royce to a completely new market, you can still get that unforgettable experience from owning the long-known luxury Rolls—', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'rolls-royce-ghost-luxury-car-review', '', '', '2022-11-19 20:21:58', '2022-11-19 17:21:58', '', 0, 'http://wordpress-carbook-training.ru/?p=688', 0, 'post', '', 0),
